Palestine responds to Israel: We will break all the agreements we have made.
Palestinian President Mahmud Abbas announced on Thursday at a session of the UN General Assembly that he would break any agreement concluded with Israel if the future government of this country tried to fulfill Benjamin Netanyahu's announcement of the annexation of occupied Palestinian lands.
"If the future government of Israel, which will arise, begins to implement this plan, we will nullify all the signed agreements (with Israel) and withdraw from all the commitments made," he announced.
"We will reject the whole plan completely and completely," he threatened with the pressure of Abbas.
"It is our duty to defend all of our rights with all possible means – not important what the consequences will be – by fully engaging in action for the application of international law and in the fight against terrorism," stated the President of the Palestinian Authority, who had already made similar declarations in July.
Netanyahu, the former Prime Minister of Israel, after the September 17 elections, was again given the mission of forming a government.
A week before the election, he announced that if he won them, he would announce the annexation of the Jordan Valley and intend to include all Jewish settlements throughout the West Bank in Israel.
In the early 1990s, Israel and the Palestinians, led by Jaser Arafat at the time, signed a series of peace agreements, which the United States was patronizing.
84-year-old Abbas also promised during the session of the UN General Assembly to hold general elections on Palestinian soils.
The last one was held in 2006.
"When I return to the country I will call upon the West Bank, Gaza Strip and East Jerusalem local elections and all who would oppose them will have to answer for their actions before God and the international community," declared the solemnly Palestinian President.
Abbas also defended in his speech the rights of Palestine, treated as a permanent observer in the UN, to exercise the powers of "full-fledged members of the UN and of all its bodies and institutions."
The Palestinian leader concluded the speech with a call to the international community to "force Israel to comply with the United Nations provisions with full respect".
Israeli Ambassador Danny Danon responded briefly to Abbas' speech, declaring that the Palestinian leader "will focus in the UN on the efforts of the Palestinian Authority against Israel rather than fight against calls for terrorism in Autonomy under his leadership."
However, Danon, as noted by the agencies, did not refer to the annexation of occupied Palestinian lands announced by Netanyahu.
