PLN 105 million for video game companies from the National Centre for Research and Development
Almost 105 million PLN of funding will be awarded to companies from the gaming industry, creating innovative solutions.
The National Centre for Research and Development announced the results of the 3rd edition of GameINN on Friday.
Among the nearly 30 projects supported by the NCBR was the development of a platform for creating field games based on an AR game engine creating a real world map together with an application that allows users to transmit data; a test and training platform to verify practical skills at work and professional improvement using VR and AI technologies; an innovative game simulating the management of real production processes using an innovative gameplay model based on the interaction of the virtual world with the real world using the concept of Industry 4.0 – given in the NCBR release sent on Friday to PAP.
The objective of the GameINN Sector Programme is to increase the competitiveness of the Polish video game industry in the global market by 2023.
According to the NCBR, the Polish video game industry is already growing at a rate of 10% per year.
According to government data, the value of the Polish video game market in 2016 amounted to PLN 1.85 billion, while the forecast for 2019 is 2.23 billion.
"The specially prepared research agenda of GameINN and the already PLN 300 million support for entrepreneurs under this sectoral programme provide an important impetus for the further dynamic growth of Polish gamedev", reads the release.
The video game industry is an excellent example of effective use of the potential we have in Poland.
"The incentives introduced by the government for entrepreneurs to invest in innovation, such as R & D reliefs, competence improvement programmes, IP box and support programmes carried out by the NCBR drive innovation activities of companies and allow them to compete more effectively on a very competitive market", says Deputy Prime Minister, Minister of Science and Higher Education Jarosław Gowin, quoted in the Communication.
The head of the Ministry of Science points out that the money for innovation not only goes to innovators in the form of project co-financing, but also stays in their pockets – three-quarters more entrepreneurs benefited from the R & D relief in 2018 than a year earlier.
"The amount of the deducted costs related to R & D activities amounted to PLN 1.7 billion, which gave over PLN 300 million savings for companies benefiting from this relief.
This is the equivalent of the support provided by the NCBR in three editions of GameINN", emphasizes the Deputy Prime Minister.
The director of NCBR Dr. Wojciech Kamieniecki reminds that 78 innovative projects were awarded in two previous competitions with a total value of over PLN 211.2 million.
A huge interest in the 3rd competition and the variety of proposals submitted show that the video game industry has ideas and competences to further develop and increase its competitive advantages.
"In particular, it welcomes the fact that the selected projects – as in previous editions – include projects on solutions for not only entertainment but also industry-related 4.0", he adds.
In the third GameINN competition, entrepreneurs, consortium of entrepreneurs with scientific units could apply for funding up to PLN 20 million.
The NCBR received 87 applications for a total amount of PLN 317 million.
The budget of the competition at the time the competition was announced was PLN 100 million, but it was increased, thanks to which 27 projects were awarded nearly PLN 105 million of co-financing.
Detailed information about the results of the 3rd GameINN competition is available at ncbr.gov.pl.
The GameINN Sector Programme is implemented under the Operational Programme Smart Development.
NCBR launched the program in 2016 in response to the initiative of entrepreneurs associated with the Polish Games Agreement, which includes companies such as CD Projekt, Techland, CI Games, Bloober Team or 11 bit studios.
