Majorca counts the losses after the bankruptcy of the travel agency Thomas Cook
Over 25,000 foreign tourists will not come to Majorca in October as a result of the bankruptcy announced on Monday by the travel agency Thomas Cook.
On Friday, according to the representative of the autonomous Balearic Government Marc Pons, among the 25 thousand holidaymakers who will not be able to take October leave in Majorca, there are also people who were to travel with companies indirectly associated with Thomas Cook, e.g. Neckermann.
Pons explained that 80 percent of the expected holidaymakers who, due to the bankruptcy of the British company, had to give up their vacation in Majorca next month are citizens of Germany and the Scandinavian countries.
However, as Pons claims, since Thomas Cook did not direct tourists to the Balearic Island during November-April, the losses to the local economy will be reduced.
He revealed that the Balearic Government had already begun negotiations with international operators on the "entry into the Majorca market" following the bankruptcy of the British operator.
According to estimates from the newspaper "Diario de Mallorca", over 1,000 people will lose their jobs due to the tourism crisis in Majorca in October.
About 800 are fired employees of the Thomas Cook office in Palma.
Other people will lose their jobs mainly in the hotel sector.
On Monday, with the announcement of bankruptcy by Thomas Cook at many Majorca hotels, the property owners demanded guests to pay an additional fee for the accommodation.
Several dozen tourists from Poland, among others, experienced this situation.
The Balearic Government estimates that by Thursday, several dozen hotels in Majorca had stopped operating at least until the end of October in connection with Thomas Cook's bankruptcy and its cooperating companies.
On the other hand, the Friday newspaper "Diario de Ibiza" indicates that most of the hotels operating in Ibiza, which have collaborated with the Thomas Cook group, are not intended to close the facilities in the coming weeks.
The newspaper recalls that on this balearic island, a British bankrupt man co-operated with 42 hotels.
On Wednesday, the autonomous Balearic authorities announced that they would ask the Spanish Government to support the region with EUR 100 million to cover losses caused by the bankruptcy by the travel agency Thomas Cook.
They revealed that the most affected tourists in this archipelago, about 36,000 people, are located in Majorca.
According to the Balearic Government data, Thomas Cook owes local tourist companies, mainly hotel operators, for the implementation of the July-September 2019 contracts of approximately EUR 5 million.
