Dakar: The largest mosque in West Africa opened
Tens of thousands of people from all over Senegal gathered on Friday in the capital for the inauguration of a huge mosque, considered the largest in West Africa.
The Muslims arrived by bus, car and foot to the Bopp district, where a new mosque stood, which could accommodate 30,000 believers.
The facility was built by the Mouride fraternity, belonging to the Sufi mainstream of Islam that dominates Senegal.
Work on the mosque began ten years ago in a wet area of six hectares, donated by the government.
The name of the mosque Massalikul Jinan (the Paths to Paradise) is derived from the poem by Sheik Ahmadou Bamba Mbacke, a 19th-century fraternity founder, venerated by his followers as a saint.
The mosque is covered with marble carrarian and has five minarets.
The highest one is 78 metres.
The mosque in the middle holds 15,000 believers, and the other one can stay on the outside esplanad.
In the richly finished interiors you can admire the gold-plated dome, giant chandeliers and hand-crafted decorations by workers from Morocco.
Builders claim that the mosque is the largest in West Africa, but the building still has no comparison to mosques in other regions.
In Morocco, the Hassan II mosque in Casablanca can accommodate 105,000 believers.
The construction of the mosque, which cost more than EUR 30 million, was funded by private donations.
In addition to land, the government has provided lighting, sanitation and financed road works worth EUR 10.5 million.
