These trees can completely disappear from Europe
"42 percent of the tree species making up the state of Europe is at risk", warns the International Union for the Conservation of Nature (IUCN) in the "Red Book of European Trees" published on Friday.
The list is headed by chestnuts and raspberries.
The IUCN, an organisation based in Gland, Switzerland, publishes a list of endangered species of European trees for the first time.
It was drawn up by experts who, on the basis of research, concluded that of the 454 tree species found in Europe (as well as elsewhere in the world), 42% are "highly endangered".
Among the causes of the Red Paper is the rapid expansion of urban agglomerations and global climate change.
However, the most endangered are those trees and shrubs that occur only or mainly on our continent.
In terms of typical European stands, according to IUCN specialists 58 percent of species are at risk, and 15 percent, i.e. 66 species of trees and shrubs, are at risk of extinction.
Among the main causes of deforestation, the Red Paper lists errors in the operation of the stand, accelerated urbanisation, too intensive logging, and subsequent forest fires and changes in the European eco-stistem.
According to the authors of the report, the existence of many European varieties of shrubs, moss and lichens is also heavily threatened.
"The consequences of human activities lead to the gradual disappearance of species of European plants and create the risk of the extinction of important and undervalued varieties in Europe, which form the basis of European ecosystems and affect the health of our planet," concluded Luc Bas, who heads the European IUCN office.
