Central Statistical Office: Poland is living better and better
According to a report on household budgets published by the Central Statistical Office on Friday, 44 percent of them were assessed as good or rather good in their material situation.
The previous year, this percentage was 37.2%, in 2016 33.5%, and earlier since 2009, when the statistical office first examined subjective assessments of households, it never exceeded 30%.
A total of 8.1% of households considered their material situation to be bad or rather bad, compared to 11.2 percent a year earlier and over 20% in 2009.
The material situation of self-employed households is best.
In this group, over 70 percent of respondents consider it good or rather good.
In the second pole there are pensioners' households, where the percentage of such responses was only 18 percent.
The subjective assessment of the material situation of households is also influenced by the number of children.
Single parent parents are the worst, with 32 percent declaring a good or rather good material situation.
Among couples with children, this percentage varies (depending on the number of children) from 55 to 60 percent, and among childless households is 48.8%.
The effect of the 500+ programme is clearly visible in these statistics.
Before it was launched (in 2016) the worst material situation was assessed by single parents and multi-children (with at least three children).
The improvement of subjective assessments of the material situation of Poles reflects the rapid increase in income, especially from work.
However, that is not all, because the percentage of households who consider their situation to be good increases faster than real income.
Moreover, there is no clear link at the level of the voivodships between the level of income and the assessment of the material conditions of households.
The best assessments are formulated by the inhabitants of the Opole Voivodeship, where 48.9 percent of respondents consider their situation to be good or rather good.
There are further Lubuskie Voivodeships (47.7%), Silesian Provinces (47.6%), Mazowieckie Provinces (47.3%) and West Pomeranian Provinces (47.1%).
Meanwhile, in Opole, disposable income (i.e. after paying taxes and contributions) amounted to less than 94% of the national average, and in Lubusek 98 percent.
The highest income was the inhabitants of Mazowiecki (120 percent of the national average) and Silesia (104%).
On average in Poland, the disposable income per person was PLN 1693 in 2018.
In real terms (after the adjustment for the impact of price changes) increased by 4.3% compared to 2017.
Against the background of previous years, that's a pretty low score.
In 2016, income per person increased by 7% and a year later by 6.3%.
Although income growth slows down, it also inhibits expenditure growth.
These per person amounted to PLN 1187 in the last year, which means that in real terms they decreased by 0.7 percent.
This is the first such case since 2013.
In 2017, expenditure per person increased in real terms by 1.9 percent, and in 2016 by 4.3 percent.
Household budget surveys suggest that the statistical household currently spends 70.1% of its disposable income, while still in 2014 this share exceeded 80%, and by 2006 it exceeded 90%.
