Belgium: Brussels Airlines cancelled 105 flights due to Thomas Cook's bankruptcy
Although British travel agency Thomas Cook has fallen, his Belgian subsidiary Neckermann functions.
However, the company has problems.
According to VRT television, Brussels Airlines announced that they would cancel 105 flights in October due to problems with Thomas Cook's bankruptcy.
Neckermann also fired 75 employees.
All trips with the office, which have been booked in Belgium, will be cancelled, but holidaymakers will be able to receive a refund.
The Ghent court also declared the bankruptcy of three Belgian daughter companies: Thomas Cook Belgium, Thomas Cook Retail and Thomas Cook Financial Services.
Currently, about 12,000 Belgians are abroad on trips purchased from Thomas Cook.
Another 40,000 people were to leave the office by the end of the year.
On Monday, spokeswoman Thomas Cook Belgium Leen Segers said that the company is now "fully operational" despite being declared bankrupt by the British company's mother, which caused concern among employees and customers.
The office then calmed down that the customers who bought the trips in it would go on vacation.
Thomas Cook – the oldest and one of the largest travel agencies in the world – declared bankruptcy on the night of Sunday on Monday.
The direct cause of the bankruptcy was the breakdown on Sunday of talks of the last chance with creditors and potential investors.
The creditors demanded that, in addition to the £900 million rescue plan already agreed on in August, the company would receive an additional 200 million as collateral for the winter period, when travel agencies usually have lower turnovers.
However, the company's problems have been growing for several years, resulting in a debt of £1.6 billion.
