Görlitz in Germany offers free accommodation for your review
Free accommodation in exchange for an opinion – such an unusual offer was prepared for German visitors Görlitz.
Actions are intended to help fight the growing decline in the number of inhabitants of the city.
Görlitz is the easternmost town of Germany.
The beautiful pastel old town attracts 140,000 tourists a year.
However, as the Guardian writes, the city faces considerable problems.
Görlitz has the lowest wages in Germany.
The city also faces a constant loss of population.
After the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, most of them left for the west of the country, which translated into a decrease in the population of the city by 25 percent.
In 2013, it amounted to 54 000 people.
To fight the depopulation, officials came up with an idea to start offering free monthly accommodation in the city.
So far, 150 applications have been received.
Two thirds of them were made up of the inhabitants of large cities.
The programme was also interested in people from Hungary, the Czech Republic, the United States and the United Kingdom.
"When we applied, we thought the program was supposed to convince people to move to Görlitz," said one of the participants in the project.
"Now we feel it doesn't matter if we stay here after four weeks or not," he added.
The city has seven thousand free housing units, and unemployment is three times higher than the average across the country.
Although the city authorities hope that some will move permanently, the main objective of the programme is to get the opinion of the participants in the programme.
The information collected from interviews and questionnaires is intended to help revive smaller German cities.
"We want to learn more about what people need, and if they decide to move – about what their motivation was," said Robert Knippschild in charge of the program.
Other cities have already experimented with ideas to lure new residents, offering them incentives in the form of accommodation.
The first was Detroit, which introduced a program to pay promising young professionals for living and working in the city for a year.
Today, such solutions are used in many places, from the Greek island of Antikythera to Candela, Italy, or in the American Tulsa, Oklahoma.
